definition: Universally Unique Identifier (UUID); a 36-character alphanumeric string unique to the occurence

Code of the scribe; most often the first initial, middle initial, and last name; refer to 'Master_Contacts .csv'
The BBL Disposition code describing the disposition of the federal metal band attached to the captured bird
The BBL Status code describing the status of the captured bird and what, if anything was done to th bird before it was released
Normal wild bird, Banding or trapping mortality

Normal wild bird, Taken from an artificial nest structure, plus auxiliary marker(s).

Normal wild bird, transmitter (use 380/381 when applicable)

Unknown condition of the bird; Band removed

Unique nest identifier associated with captured bird; based on person who found nest or nest location
Unique brood identifier; based on the flag code(s) of one or both adult(s) associated with the brood; if both adult flags codes used, identifier is formatted with a "/" seperating the codes

Identifier of the bird asociated with and presumed mating/nesting with the captured bird; identifier may be a flag code, band number, or color band combination; color bands are formatted 'UL-LL_UR_LR'

Identifier of the adult bird associated with a nest and presumed parent of the nestlings; identifier may be a flag code, band number, or color band combination; color bands are formatted 'UL-LL_UR_LR'

Identifier of the second adult bird associated with a nest and presumed parent of the nestlings; identifier may be a flag code, band number, or color band combination; color bands are formatted 'UL-LL_UR_LR'
The BBL Size code describing the size of the federal metal band attached to the captured bird
Method used to capture the bird
Age description of the captured bird
Code describing the sex of the captured bird as determined in the field
Code describing the sex of the captured bird as determined by the analysis of CHD genes
The BBL HowAged code describing how the captured bird was aged; multiple methods seperated by ','
Nestling recently fledged, incapable of powered flight
The BBL HowSexed code describing how the captured bird was sexed; multiple methods seperated by ','
Mass of captured brid in grams
No fat in the furculum or anywhere on the body
Trace; A very small amount of fat in the furcular hollow (< 5% filled)
Light; The bottom of the furculum is completely covered but the furcular hollow is less than 1/3 filled
Half; The furcular hollow is about half full, and a covering pad of fat is present under the wingpit and/or on the abdomen
Filled; The furcular hollow is full and a thick layer of fat also occurs under the wing and on the abdomen
Bulging; Fat is bulging slightly above the furculum and the fat under the wing and on the abdomen is well mounded
Greatly bulging; Fat is bulging greatly above the furculum and large mounds of fat occur under the wings and on the abdomen
Very excessive;  The fat pads of the furculum, 'wingpit,' and abdomen are bulging to such an extent that they join
Length of the head of the captured bird in millimeters; measured from tip of bill to back of head
Length from nares to tip of the captured bird in millimeters
Culmen length of the captured bird in millimeters; measured from tip of bill to base of bill
Culmen depth of the of the captured brid in millimeters; measured at the distal end of the nares
Culmen width of the captured bird in millimeters; measured at the distal end of the nares
Length of the tarsometatarsus on the captured bird in millimeters

Length of the folded wing of the captured bird in millimeters; The wing is measured in a flattened and straightened position if the bird species is in Order Charadiformes, and the wing is measured in a natural position for all other bird species (see protocol for information on how the wing length of a certain species is measured)
Length of central rectrices on the captured bird in millimeters
Gape length of the captured bird in millimeters
Length of longest primary of the captured bird in millimeters
Length of the primary 10 feather on the captured bird in millimeters; measured from skin to tip of feather
Length of the exposed primary 10 feather (out of sheathing) on the captured bird in millimeters
Length of primary 1 feather of the captured bird in millimeters
Length from primary 1 feather to lesser cover feather of the captured bird in millimeters
Length of rectrix 1 feather of the captured bird in millimeters
Cloacal protuberance score on captured bird
Small; Cloaca somewhat enlarged and noticeably swollen and the shape is conical
Medium; Cloacal protuberance large and the shape is cylindrical
Large; Cloacal protuberance very large and bulbous
Brood patch score of captured bird
Well defined, breast muscles and gut still visible through the skin
Veined and red; the skin is opaque, thickened or engorged, veined and reed with broad, undulating wrinkles
Wrinkled, the skin has thin wrinkles, engorgement of the skin has gone
Description of the eye openness of the captuered bird; applicable for nestlings
The degree of skull pneumatization on the captured bird
Skull examined but extent of pneumaticization not visible
Estimated cover of body feathers on the captured bird; percent formatted as a decimal
Whether there is color contrast on the underwing coverts of the captured bird (Y/N)
Code indicating the region where molt limits (two generations of feathers) are present on the captured bird
Body molt score of the captured bird
Trace; Only a very few feathers molting anywhere on the bird’s body in no discernible pattern.
Light; Fewer than one-third of the contour feathers on the bird are molting
Medium; From one to two-thirds of a bird’s contour feathers are in molt.
Heavy; More than two-thirds of the contour feathers on the bird are in molt.
The presence of juvenal body plumage on captured bird
Less than half of the juvenal body plumage remains.
More than half of the juvenal body plumage remains, although the bird already has begun its preformative molt.
Code describing the type of molt occuring in the flight feathers of the captured bird
The degree of feather wear on the captured bird (0-5)
The presence and characteristics of active rectrix feather molt on the captured bird
The degree of rectrix feather wear on the captured bird
Degree of rectrix feather roundness on the captured bird (0-3)
